  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the best way to clean ears?",
  "response": "Cleaning your ears properly is important for maintaining ear health and preventing issues like blockages or infections. Here are the best practices for cleaning your ears:\n\n### 1. **Avoid Inserting Objects**\n   - **Do not use cotton swabs (Q-tips)** or other objects like bobby pins or fingers to clean inside your ear canal. This can push earwax deeper, cause injuries, or even damage the eardrum.\n   - The ear canal is self-cleaning, and inserting objects can disrupt this natural process.\n\n### 2. **Let Earwax Do Its Job**\n   - Earwax (cerumen) protects your ears by trapping dust, debris, and bacteria. It naturally migrates out of the ear canal, so it doesn\u2019t usually need to be removed manually.\n   - Excessive cleaning can lead to dryness, irritation, or infections.\n\n### 3. **Clean Only the Outer Ear**\n   - Use a damp washcloth to clean the outer part of your ear (the pinna) during your regular shower or bath.\n   - Gently wipe behind your ears to remove any buildup of dirt or sweat.\n\n### 4. **Use Ear Drops for Excessive Wax**\n   - If you have a buildup of earwax causing discomfort or hearing issues, use over-the-counter **ear drops** (e.g., hydrogen peroxide, saline solution, or mineral oil-based drops) to soften the wax.\n   - Follow the instructions on the product and consult a healthcare professional if you\u2019re unsure.\n\n### 5. **Irrigation (For Stubborn Wax)**\n   - If earwax doesn\u2019t come out naturally or with drops, you can use a **bulb syringe** to gently irrigate the ear with warm water. Tilt your head, pull your ear upward to straighten the canal, and squirt water in.\n   - **Caution**: Do not use this method if you have a history of ear infections, a perforated eardrum, or ear tubes.\n\n### 6. **Seek Professional Help**\n   - If you experience ear pain, hearing loss, or a feeling of fullness in the ear, consult a healthcare provider or an ENT (ear, nose, and throat) specialist. They can safely remove earwax using specialized tools like suction or curettes.\n\n### 7. **Avoid Ear Candling**\n   - Ear candling is **not recommended** and can be dangerous. It has no proven benefits and can cause burns, injuries, or worsen earwax blockages.\n\n### Summary:\nThe best way to clean your ears is to leave the ear canal alone and focus on cleaning the outer ear. If you have concerns about earwax buildup, use ear drops or consult a healthcare professional for safe removal.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
